e instead deepening spatial contradictions and struggles. When South Durban's denizens collectively mobilized in various ways---through Black Consciousness politics and other attempts at refusing the ruinous articulation of biopolitics, sovereignty, and capital---submerged traditions of the Indian Ocean and the Black Atlantic offered them powerful resources. Of these, Chari reads Black documentary photography as particularly insightful audiovisual blues critique. At the tense interface of Marxism, feminism, and Black study, he offers a method and form of geography attentive to the spatial and embodied remains of history. Apartheid Remains looks out from South Durban to imaginations of abolition of all forms of racial capitalism and environmental suffering that define our planetary predicament.  afunded by University of California, Berkeley  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aApartheidzSouth AfricazDurban2DLC. 0aApartheidzSouth AfricazDurban. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African Studies.2bisacsh2 aUniversity of California, Berkeleyefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311135689140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478094005?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478094005zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478094005/original  a978-3-11-135689-1 Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA